{{Infobox language |name=Buyeo-Baekje |altname=Puyo-Paekche |states=[[Paekche]] |region=[[Korea]] |familycolor=altaic |fam1=[[Buyeo languages|Buyeo]] ([[Koreanic languages|Koreanic]]) |fam2= |era=5th–7th centuries |ref=linglist |iso3=xpp |linglist=xpp |glotto=none }} {{Infobox language |name=Han-Baekje |altname=Han-Paekche |states=[[Paekche]] |region=[[Korea]] |era=5th–7th centuries |ref= |familycolor=altaic |fam1=[[Han languages|Han]] ([[Koreanic]]) |fam2= |iso3=pkc |linglist2=pkc |glotto=paek1234 |glottorefname=Paekche |map=Three Kingdoms of Korea Map.png |mapcaption=The Three Kingdoms of Korea, with Baekje in green. }}
The language of the ancient kingdom of [[Baekje]] (18 BCE – 660 CE), one of the Three Kingdoms of Korea, was a Koreanic language, related to [[Goguryeo language]] and [[Silla language]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bellwood|first1=Peter|title=The Global Prehistory of Human Migration|date=2013|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|location=Malden|isbn=9781118970591}}</ref>
Since Baekje was established by immigrants from [[Goguryeo]] (the Buyeo-Baekje / Puyo-Paekche), it is presumed that they spoke the [[Goguryeo language]], and several attested words support this idea; however, even if that is true, the indigenous [[Samhan]] people (Han-Baekje) spoke [[Han languages|Han language]].<ref name="Indiana"> 2014. Multitree: A digital library of language relationships. Bloomington, IN: Department of Linguistics, The LINGUIST List, Indiana University. http://multitree.org/.</ref> or if the attested material may be a mix of Goguryeo and Samhan. The [[Gaya confederacy]], however, was founded by one of the Samhan [[tribe]]s, so it's possible that the Han-Baekje language was related to [[Gaya language|Gaya]]; it may be then that Buyeo-Baekje was related to [[Buyeo languages]], and Han-Baekje to [[Han languages]],<ref name="Indiana"></ref> which was a branch of the ancient [[Koreanic languages]].<ref name="Indiana"></ref><ref>"The World's Major Languages": Edition 2. Bernard Comrie (2017), Routledge</ref><ref name="Frawley"> "International Encyclopedia of Linguistics" (Volume 1) William J. Frawley (2003), Oxford University Press</ref><ref name="Crannell">"Voice and Articulation", Kenneth C. Crannell (2011), Wadsworth Company</ref><ref>"Studies on the phonological system of Korean", Kim Wan-jin (1981), Ilchogak</ref><ref>"Community languages: a handbook", Barbara M. Horvath, Paul Vaughan (1991), Multilingual Matters Ltd</ref>
