The '''Butonese''' (sometimes '''Butuni''', '''Butung''' or '''Wolio''') people is a generic term that embraces a number of sub-ethnic groups from [[Buton]] and its neighbouring islands in [[Southeast Sulawesi]]. Often at times the [[Bajau people]] are mislabeled as Butonese people.<ref>{{cite book|author=Natasha Stacey|title=Boats to Burn: Bajo Fishing Activity in the Australian Fishing Zone|year=2007|publisher=ANU E Press|isbn=1-920942-95-5}}</ref> The Butonese are also referred to as '''Orang Burung''', which literally means "bird people".<ref>{{cite book|author=Timothy J. O'Leary|title=Encyclopedia of world cultures: North America, Volume 1|year=1991|publisher=Hall|isbn=978-0-8168-8840-5}}</ref> Just like most tribes in Sulawesi, the Butonese people are also seafarers and traders.<ref>{{cite book|author=Aris Ananta|title=The Indonesian Crisis: A Human Development Perspective|year=2002|publisher=Institute of Southeast Asian Studies|isbn=981-230-171-2}}</ref> The Butonese people have long since migrated to all corners of the Malay archipelago using smaller vessels ranging from those that can only accommodate five people to large boats that can hold up to about 150 tons of goods. In general, the Butonese is a community that inhabits the region of the Buton Sultanate. When the ''swapraja'' (self-governance, created by the Dutch colonial government) domain was abolished, so did the Buton Sultanate also ended in 1951.<ref>{{cite book|author=Brigitta Hauser-Schäublin|title=Adat and Indigeneity in Indonesia: Culture and Entitlements between Heteronomy and Self-Ascription Göttingen Studies in Cultural|year=2013|publisher=Universitätsverlag Göttingen|isbn=3-86395-132-8}}</ref> Those regions have now changed to several regencies and cities in [[Southeast Sulawesi]]. Among them are [[Bau-Bau|Baubau City]], [[Buton Regency]], [[South Buton Regency]], [[Central Buton Regency]], [[North Buton Regency]], [[Wakatobi Regency]] and [[Bombana Regency]].

Apart from being a community of seafarers, the Butonese people are also familiar with agriculture in earlier times. Commodities that are planted include paddy, corn, cassava, sweet potatoes, cotton, coconut, betel, pineapple, banana, and all other common needs of their everyday lives. Butonese people are well known for their culture and until today it can still be seen in regions of the Buton Sultanate. Such as the fortress of the Butonese palace which is the largest fortress in the world, the Malige Palace which is a traditional Butonese house that stands firmly as high as four stories without using a single nail,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.wisatamelayu.com/en/tour/569-Malige-palace/navgeo |title=Malige palace |publisher=Wisata Melayu |accessdate=2015-01-10}}</ref> the currency of the Buton Sultanate called ''kampua'' or ''bida'',<ref>{{cite book|author=Museum Nasional (Indonesia)|title=Perjalanan Sejarah Dan Budaya Bangsa Indonesia: Koleksi Pilihan Museum Nasional|year=1995|publisher=Proyek Pembinaan Museum Nasional|oclc=34973488}}</ref> and many more.

